3.4.3. Subgroup meta-analysis
In focusing on studies with serum sample sources, six articles pro-
vided six datasets in this part of subgroup meta-analysis. The subgroup
meta-analysis suggested that serum magnesium levels in children di-
agnosed with ADHD were significantly lower than those in controls
(k = 6, Hedges' g = −0.733, 95% CI = −0.911 to −0.555, p < .001;
mean difference = −0.147 mg/dl, 95% CI = −0.224 to −0.071)
(Fig. 3A).
Furthermore, if we focused on studies using definite diagnostic
criteria in the subgroup of serum sample sources, four articles provided
four datasets for this part of the subgroup meta-analysis. All four arti-
cles used DSM-IV as the diagnostic criteria. The subgroup meta-analysis
suggested that the serum magnesium levels in children with ADHD,
diagnosed by definite diagnostic criteria, were significantly lower than
those in controls (k = 4, Hedges' g = −0.780, 95% CI = −0.985 to
−0.574,
p < .001;
mean
difference = −0.249 mg/dl,
95%
CI = −0.432 to −0.065) (Fig. 3B).
3.5. Meta-analysis of differences of magnesium levels in children with
ADHD and controls without ADHD: with regard to hair samples
Four articles provided four datasets in this part of the meta-analysis,
with three of these studies using DSM-IV as diagnostic criteria (An
et al., 2005; Baza et al., 2016; Elbaz et al., 2017) but one using DSM-5
as diagnostic criteria (Tippairote et al., 2017). The meta-analysis sug-
gested that hair magnesium levels in children diagnosed with ADHD
were significantly lower than those in controls (k = 4, Hedges'
g = −0.713, 95% CI = −1.359 to −0.067, p = .031; mean differ-
ence = −10.836 mg/kg, 95% CI = −22.120 to 0.448) (Fig. 2) with
significant heterogeneity (Q value = 20.054, df = 3, I2 = 85.041%,
p < .001) but no significant publication bias upon inspection of funnel
plot (Supplemental Fig. 2B).
3.5.1. Sensitivity test
Significant results of the meta-analysis would change to insignif-
icance after removing the datasets by An et al. (2005), Baza et al.
(2016), or Elbaz et al. (2017), which might be due to smaller sample
size after removal of any one of these studies.
3.5.2. Meta-regression and subgroup meta-analysis
None of the meta-regression and subgroup meta-analysis procedures
were performed due to insufficient datasets.
4. Discussions
The results of our meta-analysis find that peripheral blood magne-
sium levels, in either plasma, serum, or whole blood, in children di-
agnosed with ADHD were significantly lower than those in controls
(k = 8, Hedges' g = −0.547, 95% CI = −0.818 to −0.276, p < .001).
The subgroup meta-analysis with serum sample sources suggested that
the peripheral serum magnesium levels in children diagnosed with
ADHD were significantly lower than those in controls (k = 6, Hedges'
g = −0.733, 95% CI = −0.911 to −0.555, p < .001). The subgroup
meta-analysis focusing on definite diagnostic criteria suggested that the
peripheral serum magnesium levels in ADHD children diagnosed ac-
cording to DSM-IV were significantly lower than those in controls
(k = 4, Hedges' g = −0.780, 95% CI = −0.985 to −0.574, p < .001).
We also noted that magnesium levels in the hair of children diagnosed
with ADHD were significantly lower than those in controls (k = 4,
Hedges' g = −0.713, 95% CI = −1.359 to −0.067, p = .031).
These findings agree with most previous studies. However, contra-
dictory findings were made by Irmisch et al. (2011) and Antalis et al.
(2006). In the work of Irmisch et al., the first potential source of dis-
crepancy was the small sample size (9 boys in the ADHD group and 11
boys in the control group, compared to 25 cases in each of the ADHD
and control groups in Baza's study) (Baza et al., 2016). The second
potential source of discrepancy was that the blood extraction took place
