Fig. 2 indicated significantly lower peripheral blood magnesium levels, in either plasma, serum, or whole blood, for children diagnosed with ADHD than those in
controls (k = 8, Hedges' g = −0.547, 95% CI = −0.818 to −0.276, p < .001) and significantly lower hair magnesium levels in children diagnosed with ADHD than
those in controls (k = 4, Hedges' g = −0.713, 95% CI = −1.359 to −0.067, p = .031).
Y.-H. Huang et al.
Progress in Neuropsychopharmacology & Biological Psychiatry 90 (2019) 134–141
138
under two different measuring conditions. The first condition was at
rest, where there were no differences in the serum magnesium levels
between the ADHD group and the control group. The second condition
was after physiological stress (pricking stress), which resulted in a
pronounced increase of serum magnesium levels in the ADHD group
when compared to the control group. According to Galland (1991),
stress may alter the distribution of magnesium from intracellular space
to extracellular space, i.e. from the erythrocytes to serum. Furthermore,
those who suffer from magnesium deficiency may experience increased
susceptibility to physiological stress, which points to the low magne-
sium levels of ADHD children (Galland, 1991).
Moreover, our findings were also not compatible with those of
Antalis et al. (2006). As noted in Antalis' study, the first potential source
of discrepancy was the small sample size (12 cases in the ADHD group
and 12 cases in the control group, compared to 25 cases in each of the
ADHD and control groups in Baza's study) (Baza et al., 2016). The
second potential source of discrepancy was that, in Antalis' study, the
authors recruited adult patients rather than pediatric cases, which dif-
fered from the subjects of the studies included in our meta-analysis. The
final potential source of discrepancy was the high percentage of nu-
tritional supplements in Antalis' study. Compared to the 9.0% of par-
ticipants with nutritional supplements in Tippairote's study, included in
our meta-analysis (Tippairote et al., 2017), as many as 50% of ADHD
patients, compared with 25% of controls, took vitamin/mineral sup-
plements. Also, there were as many as 75% of the ADHD subjects who
were taking stimulant medication during the study period. It is well
known that these medications could increase the level of magnesium
via several mechanisms. One mechanism is by way of the regulation of
renal absorption and excretion of Mg (Schmidt et al., 1994). A second
mechanism is through urinary volume reduction, which works in-
directly by fluid intake curtailment or directly by modifications in
adrenal medullary output and renal blood flow. The third mechanism is
the discharge of Mg from the hydroxyapatite crystals of bone surfaces
caused by these medications (Schmidt, Kruesi, 1994).
