139
The association between low serum magnesium levels with ADHD
and low hair magnesium levels with ADHD may be clarified by a
number of conceivable pathophysiological mechanisms. First, magne-
sium has a repressive effect on the central and peripheral nervous
system. The reduction of the calming effect, originated by magnesium
deficiency, is one of the mechanisms of the pathophysiology of hyper-
activity (Kozielec and Starobrat-Hermelin, 1997). Magnesium plays a
role in stabilization of the electrochemical balance of cellular mem-
branes, accompanied with sodium, potassium, phosphorus and calcium
(Kozielec and Starobrat-Hermelin, 1997). In clinical situations, children
with hypomagnesemia have been described as manifesting amplified
nervous and muscular activity, together with reduced immunity from
stress, thereby bringing about irritability and decreased cognitive skills.
Magnesium is also related to the protection of cell membranes from
excitatory neurotransmitters such as glutamates (Mahmoud et al.,
2011). Magnesium regulates the glutamate N-methyl-aspartate channel,
which is related to excitotoxic cell death and apoptosis (Hariri and
Azadbakht, 2015). Second, magnesium is involved in several physio-
logical conditions. It assists in producing ATP and energy and elim-
inating ammonia from the brain, which is correlated with inattention.
Magnesium is involved in converting essential fatty acids into DHA
(docosahexaenoic acid), which is important in the process of neurode-
velopment and proper brain function (Lord and Bralley, 2008). Mag-
nesium also has an antioxidant effect, and it is thought that oxidative
stress is related to the pathophysiology of ADHD. Reducing the anti-
oxidative protection provided by magnesium might be one of the causes
of ADHD (El Adham et al., 2011). Third, magnesium is involved in
regulating neurotransmission. It is connected to the generation of ser-
otonin and dopamine by activating the rate-limiting enzyme of dopa-
mine synthesis, tyrosine hydroxylase. Dopamine and serotonin are two
important neurotransmitters related to ADHD. In short, low magnesium
levels bring about low dopamine and serotonin levels, which then play
an important role in the pathophysiology of ADHD (Villagomez and
Ramtekkar, 2014). Magnesium inhibits N-methyl-D aspartate (NMDA)-
induced norepinephrine release (Grober et al., 2015). Magnesium in-
teracts with several monoamine receptors related to the pathophy-
siology of ADHD, i.e. serotonin (5-HT1A, 5-HT2A, and 5-HT2C), nora-
drenergic (alpha 1 and alpha 2), and dopamine (D1 and D2) receptors
in animal models (Bloch and Mulqueen, 2014).
In this study, we tried to use meta-regression to examine the impact
of moderator variables on serum magnesium levels. We noted that there
was a significant inverse association between effect sizes and mean age
or mean female proportion. We are unclear about the importance of
these findings, since no previous studies have mentioned these issues.
Future studies should take these two factors into account. We are also
unsure about the causal relationship between magnesium deficiency
and the pathophysiology of ADHD for the following reasons. First, the
behavioral manifestation of ADHD, or the appetite suppressant effect
resulting from the medication used to treat ADHD may influence this
relationship (Berlin et al., 2011; Kiddie et al., 2010). Second, there have
been too few longitudinal and large cohort studies to achieve conclusive
results, and future study is needed to investigate these issues.
There were some limitations to our study. First, as for the natural
limitation of meta-analysis, we could only observe the phenomenon but
not clarify the underlying pathophysiology. Therefore, any

