2.2. Eligibility criteria
Inclusion criteria were (a) observational studies, including a cohort
or cross-sectional study design comparing peripheral levels of magne-
sium in children with ADHD and controls, and (b) trials in humans. The
exclusion criteria included: (a) preclinical studies, review articles,
meeting abstracts, and non-human studies; (b) studies not related to
magnesium levels in children with ADHD; (c) studies lacking adequate
control; and (d) studies using children not definitely diagnosed for
ADHD.
2.3. Data extraction
The two authors (BY Zeng and PT Tseng) independently extracted
data of interest following the MOOSE guidelines. Primary outcomes
were the differences in magnesium levels in children with ADHD when
compared to control groups (calculated as Hedges' g statistic and cor-
responding 95% confidence intervals (CIs) and p values). The control
groups were defined as those without ADHD. When data were not
available from ... (Extracted from Discussion)

## Methodology
Methods and materials
We
followed
the
Meta-analysis
Of
Observational
Studies
in
Epidemiology (MOOSE) guidelines (Stroup et al., 2000) (see Supple-
mental Table 1). This preliminary meta-analysis followed an a priori
defined but unpublished protocol. The current meta-analysis complied
with the requirements of the Institutional Review Board of the Kaoh-
siung Municipal Kai-Syuan Psychiatric Hospital (KSPH-N-201706).
2.1. Search strategy and study selection
Two well-trained authors (BY Zeng and PT Tseng) independently
performed a systematic literature search from the study's inception until
October 27th, 2018. The following keywords were used in our search:
“(Magnesium OR Mg) AND (attention deficit hyperactivity disorder OR
ADHD OR hyperkinesia OR hyperkinetic disorder)” on PubMed,
ProQuest, and ClinicalKey platforms. A similar search was also con-
ducted in Embase, ScienceDirect, Cochrane Library, Web of Science,
and ClinicalTrials.gov databases (Supplemental Fig. 1). The reference
lists of included articles and recent reviews were also searched to
identify additional articles (Ghanizadeh, 2013; Grober et al., 2015;
Hariri and Azadbakht, 2015; Scassellati et al., 2012; Villagomez and
Ramtekkar, 2014).
These authors (BY Zeng and PT Tseng) independently screened the
titles and abstracts of all retrieved results for potential eligibility, then
reviewed full-text articles of potentially eligible papers and compiled a
final list of included studies. Any inconsistencies were resolved through

## Results
results of our meta-analysis found that peripheral blood magnesium levels, either in plasma, serum, or whole
blood, of children diagnosed with ADHD were significantly lower than those in controls (k = 8, Hedges'
g = −0.547, 95% CI = −0.818 to −0.276, p < .001). The subgroup meta-analysis with serum sample sources
also suggested that peripheral serum magnesium levels of children diagnosed with ADHD were significantly
lower than those in controls (k = 6, Hedges' g = −0.733, 95% CI = −0.911 to −0.555, p < .001). The sub-
group meta-analysis focusing on subjects with ADHD diagnosed by definite diagnostic criteria also suggested
significantly lower peripheral serum magnesium levels in ADHD children than those in controls (k = 4, Hedges'
g = −0.780, 95% CI = −0.985 to −0.574, p < .001). We also noted that magnesium levels in the hair of
children diagnosed with ADHD were significantly lower than those in controls (k = 4, Hedges' g = −0.713, 95%
CI = −1.359 to −0.067, p = .031). In this meta-analysis, we found that children diagnosed with ADHD have
